We could try completing the square to find the minimum value, but there is an easier way. Since the coefficient of $x^2$ is positive, we know that the parabola $y=5x^2-20x+1357$ opens upward, so the vertex is the minimum point. The $x$-coordinate of the vertex is $-\frac{-20}{2\cdot 5}=2$, so plugging in $x=2$ to find the $y$-coordinate, we have $5(2)^2-20(2)+1357=\boxed{1357}.$ [asy]
Label f;

f.p=fontsize(0);

xaxis(-4,4,Ticks(f, 1.0));

yaxis(0,4,Ticks(f, 1.0));

real f(real x)

{

return 5*x^2-20*x+1357;

}

draw(graph(f,-4,4),linewidth(1));

dot((2,1357));

label("(2, 1357)", (2, 1357), NE);

[/asy]
